Conclusion
You've built a complete automation platform MVP with:

Policy Engine: Validates and enforces automation rules
REST API: Provides HTTP interface for task management
Worker System: Executes tasks asynchronously with retry logic
CLI Tool: User-friendly command-line interface
This architecture demonstrates key DevOps automation patterns: task queuing, policy enforcement, API-driven workflows, and distributed task execution. The platform can be extended with additional task types, authentication, monitoring, and scheduling capabilities for production use.

Key Takeaways:

Component integration requires clear interfaces and data contracts
Message brokers (Redis) enable asynchronous task processing
Policy engines centralize validation and business rules
Multiple interfaces (API, CLI) serve different user needs
